{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> |name = Act One |image = File:ActOne.jpg |caption = First edition |author = [[Moss Hart]] |cover_artist = |country = United States |language = English |genre = [[Memoir]], [[autobiography]] |publisher = [[Random House]] |release_date = 1959 |media_type = [[Printing|Print]] |pages = |isbn = }}
'''''Act One''''' is an autobiographical book by playwright [[Moss Hart]].<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|date=November 2012|title=The Man Who Came to Broadway|author=James Wolcott|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/culture/2012/11/moss-hart-act-one-broadway}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=2001-04-29|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Broadway Returned His Regards|author=Brad Leithauser|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/01/04/29/reviews/010429.29leithat.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title='Act One': Autobiography of Broadway Playwright Moss Hart Still Boffo 50 Years Later|author=Jonathan Yardley|date=2008-12-01|work=[[The Washington Post]]|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/11/30/AR2008113002131.html}}</ref>
==Overview== The chronicles of Moss Hart's impoverished New York childhood and his long struggle to Broadway success.
==Adaptations== The book was adapted into the film ''[[Act One (film)|Act One]]'' [[1963 in film|1963]].
[[James Lapine]] wrote a stage version (''[[Act One (play)|Act One]]''), commissioned by the Lincoln Center Theater and developed by the Vineyard Arts Project. A reading was held in July 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Theater legend gets Act 2|work=[[The New York Post]]|author=Michael Riedel|date=2012-07-19|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/theater/theater_legend_gets_act_9T5PTgad7aCe7bnJTNMgLL}}</ref> There was also a workshop on Martha's Vineyard July 16–21, 2012, which featured [[Tony Shalhoub]], [[Debra Monk]], Chuck Cooper, and David Turner.<ref>{{cite news|author=Hetrick, Adam |url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/168286-Moss-Harts-Act-One-Adapted-by-James-Lapine-Gets-Starry-Reading-With-Debra-Monk-and-Tony-Shalhoub |title=Moss Hart's 'Act One', Adapted by James Lapine, Gets Starry Reading With Debra Monk and Tony Shalhoub |work=Playbill |date=July 21, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116102344/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/168286-Moss-Harts-Act-One-Adapted-by-James-Lapine-Gets-Starry-Reading-With-Debra-Monk-and-Tony-Shalhoub |archivedate=2014-01-16 |df= }}</ref> The play premiered on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]], at the [[Lincoln Center]] [[Vivian Beaumont Theater]], in previews on March 20, 2014, with the official opening on April 17, 2014. The play starred Santino Fontana, Tony Shalhoub, and [[Andrea Martin]], and was directed by Lapine.<ref>{{cite news|author=Hetrick, Adam|author2=Gioia, Michael|last-author-amp=yes |url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/188985-Moss-Harts-Theatrical-Memoir-Act-One-With-Santino-Fontana-and-Tony-Shalhoub-Comes-to-Life-on-Broadway-March-20 |title=Moss Hart's Theatrical Memoir 'Act One', With Santino Fontana and Tony Shalhoub, Comes to Life on Broadway March 20 |work=Playbill |date=March 20, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140320172250/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/188985-Moss-Harts-Theatrical-Memoir-Act-One-With-Santino-Fontana-and-Tony-Shalhoub-Comes-to-Life-on-Broadway-March-20 |archivedate=March 20, 2014 }}</ref>
