==Marketing==
{{section-stub|date=November 2018}}
===Merchandise===

==Release==
''Kong: Skull Island'' was originally set a release date for November 4, 2016, but in December 2014, the release date was pushed back from its original release date of November 4, 2016, to March 10, 2017. The new release date coincided with the franchise's 84th anniversary. It was released in 3D and [[IMAX 3D]], as well as in [[Dolby Vision]] High Dynamic Range, and [[Dolby Atmos]] sound in Dolby Cinemas and presented in [[70mm]].<ref name=ReleaseTHR>{{cite news|last1=Ford|first1=Rebecca|title=Universal Pushes King Kong Film to 2017, Dates Great Wall Movie for 2016|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/universal-pushes-king-kong-film-757353|accessdate=December 13, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=December 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/markhughes/2017/03/06/kong-skull-island-delivers-king-sized-action-and-monster-thrills/|title='Kong: Skull Island' Delivers King-Sized Action And Monster Thrills|author=Mark Hughes|publisher=''Forbes''|accessdate=March 6, 2017}}</ref> The film premiered at the [[Empire, Leicester Square|Cineworld Empire Leicester Square]] in [[London]] on February 28, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last=Thomas |first=Kate |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-4268818/Brie-Larson-Kong-Skull-Island-premiere-London.html |title=Brie Larson at Kong: Skull Island premiere in London &#124; Daily Mail Online |publisher=Dailymail.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gettyimages.ca/event/the-european-premiere-of-kong-skull-island-arrivals-700012902#brie-larson-tom-hiddleston-and-samuel-l-jackson-attend-the-european-picture-id646342868|title=The European Premiere Of "Kong: Skull Island" – Arrivals Photos and Images {{!}} Getty Images|website=www.gettyimages.ca|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-03-03}}</ref>

===Box office===
''Kong: Skull Island'' has grossed $168 million in the United States and Canada and $398.6 million in other territories for a worldwide gross of $566.6 million.<ref name=BOM/> Made on a production budget of $185 million, with about $136 million more spent on global marketing costs, the film needed to make at least $450–500 million worldwide in order to [[break even]].<ref name="THR"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/03/kong-skull-island-logan-weekend-box-office-get-out-1202040377/|title=Sizing Up 'Kong: Skull Island's Weekend Domestic Opening|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=March 11, 2017|accessdate=March 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/box-office/box-office-kong-skull-island-rules-with-mighty-61-million-debut-1202007236/|title=Box Office: 'Kong: Skull Island' Rules With Mighty $61 Million Debut|author=Brent Lang|publisher=''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''|accessdate=March 12, 2017}}</ref>

In the United States and Canada, ''Kong: Skull Island'' was projected to gross $40–50 million in its opening weekend, as well as a worldwide debut of $110–135 million.<ref name=preview /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/03/logan-box-office-opening-get-out-the-shack-1202035207/|title='Logan' $85.3M Debut Breaks Records For Wolverine Series & Rated R Fare; Beats 'Fifty Shades' & 'Passion Of The Christ'|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|publisher=''Deadline.com''|date=March 5, 2017|accessdate=March 6, 2017}}</ref> The film made $20.2 million on its first day from 3,846 theaters, including $3.7 million it made from Thursday night previews.<ref name=opening>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/03/kong-skull-island-logan-weekend-box-office-get-out-1202040377/ |title='Kong: Skull Island' Conquering 'Logan' For Top Spot At B.O. With $53M – Midday Update|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref> In total, the film earned a better-than-expected $61 million on its opening weekend, defying the film's initial projection by 35%.<ref name="DDD">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/03/kong-skull-island-beating-box-office-projections-logan-get-out-1202041809/|title='Kong' Beats His Chest On Saturday: Weekend Opening Now At $61M – Sunday AM Update|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]''|date=March 12, 2017|accessdate=March 12, 2017}}</ref><ref name="THR">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/weekend-box-office-kong-skull-island-scales-61m-no-1-finish-985412|title=Weekend Box Office: 'Kong: Skull Island' Scales $61M for No. 1 Finish|author=Pamela McClintock|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=March 12, 2017}}</ref> In IMAX, it made $7.6 million from 382 theaters, repping 12.5% of the film's total opening weekend.<ref name="DDD"/> In its second weekend the film grossed $27.8 million (a drop of 54.4%), finishing second at the box office behind newcomer ''[[Beauty and the Beast (2017 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/03/beauty-and-the-beast-weekend-box-office-selling-out-1202045224/|title='Beauty And The Beast' $174.8M Opening Sparks Moviegoing Explosion; Pic Could Conquer 'Rogue One' & 'Dark Knight'|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=March 22, 2017}}</ref>

Internationally, the film debuted with $85.1 million from 20,900 screens in 65 markets. It opened in every market except Japan and China. In IMAX, the film scored the fourth-biggest March release with $4.8 million from 672 theaters (the second biggest without China in it).<ref name="INTL">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/03/kong-skull-island-logan-dogs-purpose-china-weekend-international-box-office-results-1202041853/|title='Kong' King In $81.6M Offshore Bow; 'Logan' Leaps To $437M Global – Intl Box Office|author=Nancy Tartaglione|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=March 12, 2017|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref> The biggest openings came from the [[United Kingdom]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] ($7.6 million), [[South Korea]] ($7.4 million), [[Russia]] ($6.2 million), [[Mexico]] ($5.7 million), [[France]] ($4.1 million), [[Taiwan]] ($3.6 million), [[Australia]] ($3.6 million), [[Brazil]] ($3.4 million), [[Germany]] ($3.4 million), [[Malaysia]] ($2.65 million), [[India]] ($2.4 million), [[Spain]] ($1.6 million) and [[Italy]] ($1.6 million), while in [[Vietnam]] (where the film was primarily shot and set), it scored the biggest opening of all time there with $2.5 million. This was the week after a huge model of the primate outside the theater caught on fire at the film's premiere.<ref name="THR"/><ref name="INTL"/> The film would eventually open in China with $71.6 million (its largest international market) and in Japan with $3.5 million, where the film was released as ''King Kong: Giant God of Skull Island'' (''Kingu Kongu: Dokurotou no Kyoshin'').<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.scifijapan.com/articles/2016/11/12/kong-skull-island-japanese-trailer-and-logo/|title= Kong: Skull Island Japanese Trailer and Logo|accessdate= November 29, 2017|work= Scifijapan.com}}</ref>
After its overseas run, the film would gross {{USD|398 million}} internationally.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&id=legendary2016.htm|title= Kong: Skull Island|accessdate= April 27, 2017|work= [[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref>

===Critical response===
''Kong: Skull Island'' received generally positive reviews from critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/kong-skull-island-fan-reviews/|title='Kong: Skull Island': What Did You Think?|last=Goldberg|first=Matt|work=Collider|date=March 10, 2017|accessdate=March 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2017/03/13/kong-skull-island-four-lessons-for-justice-league-and-the-dc-films-franchise/#40b23ec84168|title='Kong: Skull Island': Four Lessons For 'Justice League' And The DC Films Franchise|last=Mendelson|first=Scott|work=Forbes|date=March 13, 2017|accessdate=March 15, 2017}}</ref> On review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 75% based on 335 reviews, with an average rating of 6.5/10. The website's critical consensus reads, "Offering exhilarating eye candy, solid acting, and a fast-paced story, ''Kong: Skull Island'' earns its spot in the movie monster's mythos without ever matching up to the classic original."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/kong_skull_island |title=Kong: Skull Island (2017) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=September 8, 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 62 out of 100, based on 49 critics, indicating "generally favorable reviews".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/kong-skull-island |title=Kong: Skull Island Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of "B+" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name="CinemaScore">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/CinemaScore/status/840452223805095936 |title=''Kong: Skull Island'' |publisher=[[CinemaScore]] on [[Twitter]] |date=March 10, 2017 |accessdate=April 10, 2017}}</ref>

[[Michael Phillips (critic)|Michael Phillips]] of ''[[The Chicago Tribune]]'' lauded the film, giving it three-and-a-half stars out of four: "I saw little in [Vogt-Roberts'] [[The Kings of Summer|first feature]] to indicate the deftness and buoyant spirit he brings to ''Skull Island''. This time, the money's on the screen, but it bought a really good movie, too."<ref name="CinemaScore2">{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-kong-skull-island-mov-rev-0307-20170307-column.html |title='Kong: Skull Island' review: Big budget buys dazzling effects and a really good movie too |publisher=[[The Chicago Tribune]]|date=March 8, 2017 |accessdate=May 30, 2017}}{{rating|3.5|4}}</ref> Mike Ryan of ''[[Uproxx]]'' gave the film a positive review, noting, "''Kong: Skull Island'' is still a hoot. It was a movie that was not at all on my radar as something I was dying to see and yet I had way too much fun watching it. I just wished it had embraced its craziness just a little bit more. (But, yes, there's still plenty of crazy to go around.)"<ref>{{cite web |last=Ryan|first=Mike|url=http://uproxx.com/movies/kong-skull-island-review/ |title='Kong: Skull Island' Is Ridiculous Fun |website=Uproxx |date=March 2, 2017|accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref> [[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' gave the film a positive review as well, stating that "all the requisite elements are served up here in ideal proportion, and the time just flies by, which can rarely be said for films of this nature."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/kong-skull-island-review-982156|title='Kong: Skull Island': Film Review}}</ref> Kyle Anderson of ''[[Nerdist News]]'' found the film entertaining but flawed, saying, "It's certainly not a perfect movie, and a lot of the characters feel like sketches more than fully-fledged people, but it roars along enjoyably from start to finish."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nerdist.com/kong-skull-island-is-big-raucous-monster-fun-review/|title=KONG: SKULL ISLAND IS BIG, RAUCOUS MONSTER FUN (REVIEW)}}</ref>

Conversely, [[Peter Bradshaw]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' awarded the film one out of five stars. In his negative review, he described the movie as a "fantastically muddled and exasperatingly dull quasi-update of the King Kong story."<ref>{{cite web |last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/mar/02/kong-skull-island-tom-hiddleston-review-only-de-evolution-can-explain-this-zestless-mashup |title=
Kong: Skull Island review – only de-evolution can explain this zestless mashup |website=The Guardian |date=March 3, 2017|accessdate=March 3, 2017}}{{rating|1|5}}</ref> Matthew Lickona of ''[[The San Diego Reader]]'' also gave the film one out of five stars, writing: "It's fun to watch [the monsters] in action, but on the human side, the film is clumsily written, over-cast and underacted, with only frustrated soldier Samuel L. Jackson striking the right tone of crazy amid the chaos."<ref>{{cite web |last=Lickona|first=Matthew|url=https://www.sandiegoreader.com/movies/kong-skull-island/# |title=KONG: SKULL ISLAND 1.0 STARS|website=The San Diego Reader |date=March 2017|accessdate=May 30, 2017}}{{rating|1|5}}</ref> Chris Klimek of ''[[NPR]]'' mentions how "''Kong'' is at its mediocre best when it pretends to be a nature documentary about Skull Island's bizarro flora and fauna," but lamented how "every time the movie threatens to get interesting, one of its hordes of ersatz, non-animated characters shows up and starts talking again."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Klimek|first1=Chris|title=In The Forgettable 'Kong: Skull Island,' A Great Cast, Cast Aside|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/03/09/518778017/in-the-forgettable-kong-skull-island-a-great-cast-cast-aside|website=NPR.org|language=en|date=March 9, 2017}}</ref> [[Anthony Lane]] of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' noted that what the film "yearns to be, is a pop-culture ''[[Apocalypse Now]]'', with the human foe removed, the political parable toned down, and the gonzo elements jacked up."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lane|first1=Anthony|title=The Current Cinema: "Kong: Skull Island"|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/03/13/kong-skull-island-and-raw|website=The New Yorker|publisher=Condé Nast|date=March 13, 2017}}</ref> J.R. Jones questioned the film's setting, saying "this ''[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]'' knockoff takes place neither in the Depression era, which gave us the original ''[[King Kong (1933 film)|King Kong]]'', nor in the present, when satellite photos would surely alert us to the existence of a 100-foot gorilla. Instead—and for no reason I can fathom, except perhaps the classic-rock tunes desired for the soundtrack—the story takes place in 1973, when the Vietnam war is winding down and President Nixon is being driven from office."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jones|first1=J.R.|title=Kong: Skull Island|url=https://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/kong-skull-island/Film?oid=25527309|website=Chicago Reader|language=en}}</ref>

Several critics have commented on Larson's role in the movie, as she had recently won an Academy Award for [[Room (2015 film)|''Room'']],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hornaday|first1=Ann|title=Hollywood ageism punishes actresses, but the art house offers some hope|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/hollywood-ageism-punishes-actress-but-the-art-house-offers-some-hope/2017/03/09/ce7e0e24-040c-11e7-ad5b-d22680e18d10_story.html|accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref> with Michael Salfino of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' remarking that "a starring role in a popcorn movie on the heels of a passion project can open up an actor to ridicule."<ref>Salfino, Michael (March 9, 2017) "The Post Oscar popcorn Film" ''The Wall Street Journal'' page A13</ref>

